 destruction. Both the Anthropocene and the war on terror centered the antagonist figures of the Anthropos and the terrorist as responsible for epochal changes in the new geological and geopolitical world orders. In response, Mameni shows how the Terracene requires radically new engagements with terra (the earth), whose intelligence resides in matters such as oil and phenomena like earthquakes and fires. Drawing on the work of artists whose practices interrogate histories of settler-colonial and imperial interests in land and resources in Iran, Iraq, Yemen, Kuwait, Syria, Palestine, and other regions most affected by the war on terror, Mameni offers speculative paths into the aesthetics of the Terracene.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aArts and societyzMiddle East. 0aArts, ModernxPolitical aspectsy21st century. 0aArts, Moderny21st centuryxPolitical aspects. 0aClimatic changesxSocial aspects. 0aEnvironmental degradation in art. 0aHuman ecology in art. 0aTerrorismxEnvironmental aspects. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009, in mass media. 0aWarxEnvironmental aspects. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027041?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027041423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027041/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles